Germany, year zero
May 8th always reminds me of 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was truly a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistor, would return from the Brandebourg prison.
I wouldn't have to hide anymore after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
This was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry I got from a bookstore.
I was sixteen. The occupation armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin and charged with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate matter, even if for our family it was undoubtedly a liberation in every sense of the word.
But why?
For what future?
“You must help,” my mother said to me.
I offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to some distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card for "victim of fascism," while others wore a Cross of Honor obtained for late service to the army.
Some were East German refugees, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the loss of relatives.
Yet, this phase did not last.
It's almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupation powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and particularly accompanied by a new form of enslavement.
Camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled enhancement of autonomy.
A year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
The democracy was not a mere empty word, and it relied on German traditions.
Indeed, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
This was also the beginning of the Cold War, and everyone wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of economic order, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy undoubtedly takes root more easily in an economic recovery context.
For this, above all, there needs to be initiative, from individuals willing to put an end to a period of hardship.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (like those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Which is why the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan is significant.
Similarly, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries, and continues to accompany them in their process.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders indisputable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey by focusing on the past.
In fact, many have described the years after 1949 under Adenauer as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
From a certain point of view, the country was ignoring its past to move towards the future.
Much later, after establishing a market economy and political democracy, Germany faced its past with great success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other traumatised countries thus cause confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, 8 May 2005 is an opportunity to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and thus filled with hope.
